        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent</hi></placeName>
                    <date>May 10. 76</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for the honour of your letter of May 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>, and for the Memoir which you have addressed to me; but I much regret that it has never reached me.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I am very sorry for this, as the foliation of rocks formerly interested me greatly, and there can be no doubt that you will throw a flood of light on this whole subject, as on so many other subjects. If however your essay has been addressed to the Geolog: Soc of London, it may not be lost, as parcels are generally transmitted to me from the Society in a bundle.</p>
<p>With the highest respect | I remain | dear Sir | Yours faithfully | &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Daubrée’s <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10496.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 4 May 1876</ref> has not been found, but his memoir on schistose foliation in rocks that had undergone intense metamorphism (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9269.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Daubrée 1876</ref>) is in the Darwin Pamphlet Collection–CUL. CD had discussed foliation in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>, pp. 165–6; in 1876, he was preparing a second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref> (published as part of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2807.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Geological observations</hi> 2d ed.</ref>), but he made no mention of Daubrée’s work.</note>
            </div>        
            
